{'Unordered list': [[{'text': 'For lifting and shifting existing applications to Azure.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure App Services', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'One of the easiest and most powerful ways to host your applications in Azure is in Azure', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'App Service. Azure App Service is a group of services that takes care of hosting your', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'application and abstracting away the complexities of the operating system and', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'infrastructure. They are highly available by default and will stay up and running for at', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'least 99.95% of the time.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '7', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'They share powerful features like automatic scaling, zero-downtime deployments, and', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'easy authentication and authorization. They also allow you to debug your application', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'while it is running in production (with the Snapshot Debugger) and work very well with', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Application Insights, which you can use to monitor every aspect of your app, from', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'performance to usage.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'There are several different types of App Service apps.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Web Apps', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Running a .NET web application in Azure is very easy in Azure Web Apps. Web Apps act', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'as a web server as a service, like IIS. And you can simply deploy your ASP.NET or', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'ASP.NET Core application with Visual Studio to Web Apps and run it. These can be', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'websites, APIs, or any other HTTP-driven application including Node.js, Python and Java', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'applications.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Once your application runs in an App Service web app, you can scale it up or down, add', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'easy authentication, use deployment slots, enable continuous deployment, and use any', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'of the other App Service features. By default, your application is available on the', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'internet, without you needing to set up a domain name or configure DNS settings,', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'although you can do that.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Try it now  -  Get started by creating an ASP.NET Core web app in Azure', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Containers on App Services', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Developers who want the power of App Services but need to maintain a higher level of', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'control over their environments can also run containers.  Both Linux and Windows', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'containers are supported. You can deploy your own containers from the Azure', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Container Registry, a private Docker registry or public containers from the Docker Hub.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'This allows you to run a wide range of pre-configured applications from WordPress to', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Redis which can be deployed either as single containers or as part of a multi-container', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'application. Windows container support also helps you migrate existing ASP.NET apps', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'and WCF services that need access to the Windows OS, install custom components, or', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'use the Global Assembly Cache (GAC).', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '8', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Mobile Apps', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'If you are building mobile applications, you will need a back end that the mobile app', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'connects to. Usually, this is some sort of API that your app can use to retrieve and store', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'data. Azure Mobile Apps provides you with such a back end. You can write it in C# or', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'use any of the Quickstart applications.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'A mobile back end that runs in Azure Mobile Apps provides unique capabilities. For', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'instance, you can use offline sync, which enables the mobile app to continue working', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'when there is no connection to the back end and sync changes once the connection is', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'restored. And with push notifications you can send notifications to the mobile apps', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'using C# code, regardless of the platform it runs on (iOS, Android, Windows). In addition', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'to these unique features, Mobile Apps shares all the other features of Azure App Service.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Get started by creating an Android app with an Azure mobile app back end .', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Functions (also known as serverless compute)', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Function apps enable you to create Azure Functions in C# and many other', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'languages in Visual Studio and other IDEs and editors. Each Functions app contains one', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'or more Azure Functions and provides integration with authentication and deployment', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'slots.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'The Azure Functions that run in Azure Function apps are small pieces of code that you', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'write, without you having to worry about the underlying infrastructure or about scaling.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Many refer to this deployment model as Functions as a Service (FaaS).', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Function applications can be simply triggered by a wide variety of events originating', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'both inside and outside of Azure. HTTP triggers allow web requests to be served by a', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'function app. Event Grid events can trigger Azure Functions when changes are made to', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure resources such as the container registry and virtual machines.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '9', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Here is an example: You write an Azure Functions app that executes every time a new', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'image file is uploaded to Azure Storage. You then take that image, rename it, and', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'output it to another Azure Storage account.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'This is very easy to do. You just write the code to rename the image. Azure Functions', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'takes care of getting the input image when the function is triggered. And it takes care of', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'writing the image to the other storage account. It takes care of all the plumbing, and', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'you just write the code.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure  Functions  even  handles  scaling  for  you.  So  it  doesn’t  matter  if  there  are  1,000', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'images that trigger the function at the same time. Azure Functions transparently spins up', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'more  functions  to  deal  with  it  and  they  go  away  when  the  code  is  done  executing.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Because of this, you only pay for the code that you execute, not for a service that runs all', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'the time, waiting to be triggered.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Functions are great for executing small pieces of code that perform one or two', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'steps on an input and an output. If you want to perform more steps of a larger process,', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'you can use Durable Functions.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Durable Functions provide a stateful experience on top of a series of Azure Functions.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'They enable complex patterns such as scatter/gather and function chaining. A Durable', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Function orchestration may be as simple as coupling together two functions, one after', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'another, or as complex as coordinating tens of thousands of function calls over weeks.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Get started by creating your first Azure Function with Visual Studio .', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Logic Apps', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Durable Functions are a fantastic orchestration tool for developers who are comfortable', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'with writing every step of the process inside a series of Functions. For those looking for', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'a lower code solution Logic Applications may be better. With Azure Logic Apps, you can', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'orchestrate a process just by weaving API calls together in a visual designer in Visual', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Studio or the Azure portal. Visual Studio offers a specific Logic Apps project template to', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'get started.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '10', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'A logic app has a trigger, just like an Azure function does. This can be an outside trigger,', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'like when a new blob is added, or a certain text is tweeted. Or it can be a manual trigger', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'or a trigger on a schedule such as every 15 minutes.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Once triggered, a logic app takes its input and calls APIs with it to complete a process.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'You just click this together by choosing APIs from a large list of available ones and', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'choosing the input and output for those APIs. Azure Functions can also be used for APIs', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'in a logic app. And you can use your own ASP.NET Core APIs.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Here’s an  example :', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'A logic app gets triggered by a new blob that is written in  Azure Blob storage . It takes the', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Blob input, which is an image file, and resizes the image by calling an Azure function that', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'does just that. Next, it takes the resized image and writes it to another storage account.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'And finally, it calls the   Office 365 API   to send an email to the administrator that there is a', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'new, resized image available.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Just like Azure functions, logic apps scale automatically, you just create the process. It will trigger as\nmany times as it is needed and always executes the complete process and has reliability features, like\nretry policies, built in. And because it only runs when it is triggered, you only pay for when it runs—you\ndon’t pay for owning it.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Get started by building your first logic app workflow in the Azure porta l .', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Note: Azure Logic Apps and Azure Functions work very well with the Azure Event Grid service. Event Grid allows you to\nsubscribe to events, like when something happens in your application, and to push that information as an event that can\ntrigger a Logic App or an Azure Function.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Virtual Machines', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'A very different way of running your application is by taking advantage of Azure Virtual', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Machines. This is an easy way to get started, because you can lift-and-shift existing', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'applications from virtual machines that you run in your datacenter to VMs that run in', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure. There are many predefined VM images that you can use, like Windows Server', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '2019 that runs IIS and has ASP.NET installed and preconfigured on it. You can even', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'bring your own software licenses if you already have one (like for SQL Server).', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '11', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Running your application in a VM doesn’t provide you the features like zero-downtime', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'deployments and easy authentication. You are also responsible for patching the', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'operating system and for making sure that antivirus software is up to date.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'On the other hand, it does provide you with the ability to easily scale your VM to a', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'bigger size or automatically scale it down when it isn’t used that much. Virtual Machine', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Scale Sets allow for scaling out VMs to a large number of nodes and load balancing', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'work between them. And it offers you the reliability of running something in Azure. It is', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'very unlikely that your VM will stop running, and Microsoft guarantees this uptime with', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'a comprehensive SLA.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'And if you’re not ready to run your production VMs in Azure you can still take', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'advantage of streamlined DevOps and testing with Azure DevTest Labs.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Get started by Creating a Windows virtual machine with the Azure portal .', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'A word about microservices and containers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'You can run your applications in containers, which are very lightweight and start and', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'stop in seconds. Containers isolate your application and its dependencies in a way that', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'guarantees that you’ll never run into library version conflicts. They can be based on', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'numerous popular Linux distributions or Windows Server so no matter the platform your', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'application uses it can run in a container.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'A popular approach for containers is to use them to run a microservices architecture.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'This means that you create many small, isolated, services that each have their own', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'function and each have separate development and deployment lifecycles. Containers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'can also be used to lift and shift existing applications to run at scale in the cloud.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure provides several services to support running a microservices architecture in', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'containers. Running the increasingly popular orchestration engine Kubernetes, Azure', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Kubernetes Service (AKS) provides a powerful tool to run anything from a handful of', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'containers to hundreds of thousands of them. AKS can all run and orchestrate', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'containers. Orchestration of containers is quite different from orchestrating a process,', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'like Logic Apps does. Orchestrating containers means that you manage their lifecycles.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Provision new ones, scale up or down, manage failures, and so on.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '12', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'You can learn more about microservices by reading:', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '.NET Microservices Architecture Guidance', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Which frameworks and technologies can you use in which Azure service?', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Now that you know what the options are for running your application in Azure, it is', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'extremely useful to know which version of .NET you can run in these services and what', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'kind of containers they support. Table 2 explains this by showing which framework and', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'container types you can use in which services in Azure.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Table 2: Which framework and technology can you use in which Azure service', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Web Apps', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Mobile\nApps', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Functions', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure VMs', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure\nContainer\nInstance', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure\nKubernetes\nService\n(AKS)', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '.NET Framework\napps', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '.NET Core apps', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Linux Containers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Windows Server\nContainers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '13', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Storing your data in Azure\nData is a particularly important aspect of any modern .NET application, and it comes in', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'all shapes and sizes. Azure provides many types of data stores that can help you', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'maintain and retrieve data in any scenario.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Table 3 shows which data service to use for which scenario.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Database', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Cosmos DB', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Blob', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Table', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'File', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'PostgreSQL,\nMySQL', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'SQL Data\nWarehouse', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Data Lake\nStore', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Relational data', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Unstructured\ndata', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Semistructured\ndata', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Files on disk', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Store large data', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Store small\ndata', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Geographic\ndata\nreplication', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Tunable data\nconsistency', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '14', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure SQL Database', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'If you are familiar with .NET, you will likely be familiar with SQL Server. In Azure, you can', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'run your SQL Server workload in Azure SQL Database. This is SQL Server in the cloud. It', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'is the same thing that you run on-premises but it offers a lot of advantages.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'You can do (almost) everything with it that you can do with on-premises SQL Server.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'And, in fact, new SQL Server features are incorporated in Azure SQL Database first and', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'later in the on-premises SQL Server.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'You can use Azure SQL Databases with your favorite tools, like Azure Data Studio, Server', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Explorer and SQL Server Data Tools in Visual Studio and SQL Server Management', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Studio.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Because they run in the cloud, Azure SQL Databases are fully managed, scalable, and', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'high performing. They are automatically backed up and have many advanced features,', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'such as:', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '•  Single-click Geo-replication, which replicates data to other geographical regions in', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'real time, incredibly easily.  (Get started with geo-replication.)', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '•  Dynamic data masking, which masks sensitive data for certain users at runtime.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '(Get started with dynamic data masking.)', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '•  Auditing, which provides a complete audit trail of all the actions that happen to the', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'data. (Get started with Azure SQL Database auditing.)', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '•  Automatic database tuning, which monitors the performance of your database and', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'tunes it automatically. (Get started with Azure SQL Database automatic tuning.)', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '15', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'In addition to all these features, Azure SQL Databases are exceptionally reliable by', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'default. Without configuring anything, transaction log backups are made every 5-10', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'minutes and differential backups every 12 hours. These backups are stored three times', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'in the local datacenter and three times in another datacenter. And you can restore', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'backups from 35 days ago, depending on the pricing tier that you use.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'It is very easy to use Azure SQL Databases from a .NET application. You can, for instance,', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'use the Entity Framework (or Entity Framework Core) to access the database and write', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'and read data to and from it. For the most part accessing data programmatically is no', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'different from accessing data in an on-premises SQL Server.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Get started by creating an Azure SQL Database in the Azure Portal .', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Cosmos DB', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Cosmos DB is a new kind of database that is globally distributed and cloud native.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Here are some of its key features:', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '•  A 99.99% SLA (99.999% for read operations) that includes low latencies (less than 10', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'ms on reads; less than 15 ms on writes).', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '•  Geo-replication, which replicates data to other geographical regions in real time', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '(How to distribute data globally with Azure Cosmos DB).', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '•  Tunable data consistency levels, so you can choose data consistency, enabling a', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'truly globally distributed data system. You can, for instance, choose strong', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'consistency, eventual consistency, or session consistency.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '•  Traffic management, which sends users to the data replica to which they are closest.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '•  Limitless global scale. You pay only for the throughput and storage that you need.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '•  Automatic indexing of data. No need to maintain or tune the database anymore.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'In addition to all these features, Cosmos DB offers different APIs with which you can', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'store and retrieve data, including SQL, Gremlin, MongoDB, Azure Table Storage, and', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Apache Cassandra. Different APIs handle data in different ways. You can use documents', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'as data as well as unstructured tables, graphs, and blobs. You use the API that fits your', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '16', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'needs, and Cosmos DB takes care of the rest. If your application already uses one of', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'these protocols switching to Cosmos DB is as simple as changing a connection string.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'You benefit from cloud-grade performance, scalability, and reliability, and still use the', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'programming model to which you’re accustomed.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'You can use Cosmos DB from .NET Framework and .NET Core. For example, you can use', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'its SQL API through the NuGet package Microsoft.Azure.DocumentDB or', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Microsoft.Azure.DocumentDB.Core (for .NET Core).', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Get started with Azure Cosmos DB with the SQL API and .NET Core .', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Storage', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'With Azure Storage, one of the most fundamental services in Azure, you can store data', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'in different forms. It is easy to use, fast, and inexpensive. Azure Storage offers several', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'types of storage that you can use for different scenarios. All these storage types share', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'common features like encryption for data at rest, security through shared access', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'signatures, and firewalls and virtual networks.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Storage is also very reliable. By default, data is replicated three times within the', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'datacenter. You can also choose geo-replicated storage, which, in addition to the three', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'local replicas, replicates the data three times to another datacenter. You can create your', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'application in such a manner that it reads from this geo-replicated data, which is close', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'to your users, so that it is geographically high performing.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'You can use Azure Storage from your .NET Framework and .NET Core applications by', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'using the WindowsAzure.Storage NuGet package and referencing the specific API that', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'you need, like Microsoft.WindowsAzure.Storage.Blob (for Blob storage) in a using', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'statement in your code.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '17', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Let’s explore the different types of Azure Storage:', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'File Storage', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure File storage uses the SMB protocol, which makes it very suitable for  lifting and', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'shifting your file server into the cloud. When you have files in Azure Files, you can mount', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'an Azure file share to a VM or even to your own Windows machine, to use as external', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'storage.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Get started with Azure Files .', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Disk Storage is a similar service to Azure File but is dedicated to a single machine.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'It is available in four different performance levels from Standard HDD to Ultra SSD. The', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'high performance tiers are suitable for heavy I/O workloads such as running SAP HANA', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'or complex analytical models.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Table Storage', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Table storage is an inexpensive and extremely fast NoSQL key-value store that', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'you can use to store data in flexible tables. A table can contain one row describing an', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'order and another row describing customer information. You don’t need to define a', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'data schema. This makes Table Storage very flexible.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Get started with Azure Table storage .', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Blob Storage', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'You can use Azure Blob storage to store large unstructured data—literally, blobs of data.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'This can be video, image, audio, text, or even virtual hard drive (VHD) files for VMs.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Additionally, you can use Blob tiers to reduce your storage costs. By default, blobs are', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'written to the hot tier, which means that they are written and read very fast. You can', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'also put blobs in the cool tier if you have data that is infrequently accessed and stored', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'for at least 30 days. The cool tier is less expensive than the hot tier. And finally, you can', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'store blobs in the archive tier, that is the least expensive. The archive tier is for data', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '18', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'that is rarely accessed and stored for at least 180 days. Reading data from the archive', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'tier can take hours. Blob tiering is a great way to save costs if you are storing large', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'amounts of data.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Get started with Azure Blob storage .', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Queue Storage', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure  Queue  storage  is  an  unusual  type  of  storage  in  that  it  is  used  to  store  small', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'messages of data, but its main purpose is to serve as a queue. You put messages on the', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'queue and other processes pick it up. This pattern decouples the message sender from', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'the message processor and results in performance and reliability benefits. Azure Queue', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'storage is similar to Microsoft Message Queuing that you can find in Windows.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Get started with Azure Queue storage .', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '|Note: Azure Service Bus Topics and Queues also provide queuing mechanisms, with slightly different properties than Azure Storage\nqueues.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Databases for MySQL, PostgreSQL, and MariaDB', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'As a .NET developer, you encounter many different open-source database types in your', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'job. Some of them can now be used in a managed version in Azure.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure provides MySQL, PostgreSQL, and MariaDB databases as managed databases,', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'which means that you just spin them up and don’t have to worry about any of the', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'underlying infrastructure. Just like Azure SQL Databases and Cosmos DB, these', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'databases are universally available, scalable, highly secure, and fully managed.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Each of these is suited for slightly different use cases, but in general, their functionality', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'overlaps a lot. You would use Azure Databases for MySQL, PostgreSQL, and MariaDB', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'when you are already using one of their on-premises versions and want the advantage', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'of having that run fully managed in the cloud. Migrating apps that use these databases', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'is much easier when the data can remain in its original platform. Azure also provides an', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'out of the box backend for services like WordPress which rely on open source databases.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '19', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Get started with Azure Database for MySQL by creating a MySQL server', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'by using the Azure porta l .', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure SQL Data Warehouse and Azure Data Lake Store', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Since we are talking about storing data in Azure, we can’t leave out the data stores for', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'big data and data analytics. These are not typical stores that you use with your', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'application, but rather stores that you use for data analytics and reporting.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure provides two data stores that are very suitable for storing large amounts of data', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'for data analytics purposes: the Azure SQL Data Warehouse and the Azure Data Lake', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Store.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Each of these can hold petabytes of data. In fact, Azure Data Lake Store doesn’t even', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'have limits on the amount of data and the file sizes that you can store.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'You use Azure SQL Data Warehouse when you know the questions that you want to', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'answer with data analytics. You define a data schema that determines what your data', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'will look like and how it can be used.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'You use Azure Data Lake Store when you don’t know the questions that you want to', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'answer yet. You do not have to define a data schema for the Data Lake Store. You store', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'data in its native format.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'You can work with each of these data stores with tools in Visual Studio. And you can use', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'any SQL tool, like SQL Server Management Studio, to work with Azure SQL Data', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Warehouse. You can even create eye-popping business intelligence dashboards and', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'reports as a non-developer in Power BI.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Additionally, you can use the Azure Management SDK for .NET to perform management', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'operations on these services. You can, for instance, create a new Data Lake Store', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'account.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Get started with Azure SQL Data Warehouse by creating and query', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'a warehouse in the Azure portal .', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '20', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Get started with Azure Data Lake Store using the Azure portal .', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Securing your .NET applications in Azure\nBesides running your application and storing data, you need to secure it. Azure can help', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'you  with  that  by  providing  authentication  and  authorization  through  Azure  Active', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Directory  and  by  helping  you  to  keep  secrets  safe  with  Azure  Key  Vault  and  inserting', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'credentials  into  your  application  with  Managed  Service  Identity.  Let’s  examine  these', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'services.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Active Directory', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'An important part of your application’s security is authenticating users before they can', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'use it. Authentication is not an easy thing to implement. You need to store user', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'identities and credentials, implement password management, create a secure', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'authentication handshake, and so on.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Active Directory provides all these things and more out of the box. You store your', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'user identities in Azure Active Directory and have users authenticate against it,', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'redirecting them to your application only after they are authenticated. Azure Active', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Directory takes care of password management, including common scenarios like “I', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'forgot my password.” Azure Active Directory is used by millions of applications every', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'day, including the Azure portal, Outlook.com, and Office 365. Because of this, it is able', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'to more readily detect malicious behavior and act on it. For instance, if a user were to', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'sign in to an application from a location in Europe and then one minute later sign in', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'from Australia, Azure Active Directory would flag this as malicious behavior and ask the', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'user for additional credentials through multifactor authentication.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'To programmatically talk to Azure Active Directory, you can use the Active Directory', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Authenticating Library (ADAL) for .NET Framework and .NET Core.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '21', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Get started by integrating Azure AD into an ASP.NET Core web app', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Key Vault', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'It is important to keep secrets such as passwords and connection strings out of source', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'code. So where do you put them? In Azure Key Vault.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Key Vault is a safe place to store passwords, connection strings, access codes,', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'and certificate keys. It is fully managed by Azure, so you don’t have to worry about', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'the underlying infrastructure. You just spin it up and use it.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'You can use it as a configuration store in your applications, just like you would use a', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'web.config file. An administrator can populate the values in the Azure Key Vault, and', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'your application just pulls it out at startup time or whenever it needs it. This way,', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'passwords will never be in source code and are the responsibility of the Azure Key Vault', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'administrator.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'You can use Azure Key Vault using the Microsoft.Azure.KeyVault NuGet package that', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'you can use from the .NET Framework and .NET Core. There is even a special syntax', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'which allows pulling secrets from KeyVault in App Services with zero code changes. For', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'more complex scenarios where configuration changes based on location, release or', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'some other custom dimension Microsoft is introducing Azure App Configuration a', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'service dedicated to providing a centralized configuration location which can be used', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'from everything form App Services to a DevOps pipeline.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Get Started by using Azure Key Vault from an ASP.NET application', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Managed Service Identity', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Even when you use Azure Key Vault, your application must have some credentials in its', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'configuration. Something that you use to connect to Azure Active Directory or to Azure', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Key Vault. Well, it doesn’t have to anymore. You can now  use Azure Managed Service', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Identity.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '22', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'You can use Managed Service Identity from a lot of services in Azure, including from', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure App Service. From there, you can enable it to inject credentials into your', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'application at runtime and use those credentials to access other services, like Azure Key', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Vault.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'You can use the Managed Service Identity from the .NET Framework and .NET Core', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'using the Microsoft.Azure.Services.AppAuthentication NuGet package.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Get started by using Key Vault from App Service with', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Managed Service Identity .', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Advisor', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'There are a lot of moving parts in Azure so Microsoft provides a tool called Azure', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Advisor which examines your Azure resources and makes recommendations. The', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'recommendations include how to save money by making more efficient use of Azure', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'resources and suggestions on how to make your Azure resources more secure. The', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'security advisor will catch and rank problems like world readable Blob Storage and give', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'instructions on how to better secure your environment.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Other Azure services\nEnhance your application performance', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure can also help you to boost your applications’ performance. One service that helps', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'with this is Azure Redis Cache, which provides high-performance, in-memory, key-value', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'storage. Another is Azure Content Delivery Network, or CDN, which can replicate your', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'static content, like images and video files to points-of-presence all over the world,', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'making sure that it is as close to your users as possible. And finally, Azure Traffic', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Manager can improve application responsiveness by routing users to locations with the', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'lowest latency.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Machine Learning', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure provides an industry leading suite of services that can make your application more', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'intelligent. Azure Cognitive Services are a suite of APIs that can do things which would', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'be nearly impossible using traditional programming approaches. You can  quickly build', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '23', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'applications  which  can  recognize  faces,  convert  speech  to  text  and  understand  the', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'meaning of text. Using the Language Understanding service you can create bots which', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'can intelligently respond to requests in Slack, Microsoft Teams and other forums.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'You can also create your own machine learning algorithms with Azure Machine Learning.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Training jobs created in popular tools such as Tensorflow can be submitted to run on a', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'cluster of GPU-enabled Virtual Machines, vastly decreasing the time to train models.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Internet of Things (IoT)', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'When you are building a solution based on the Internet of Things, Azure can help you', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'with services like Azure IoT Hub, which can ingest massive amounts of messages from', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'IoT devices and manage the devices. Azure IoT Suite makes it possible for you to', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'manage your IoT devices without doing everything yourself. And if you have limited IoT', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'experience, you can use Azure IoT Central, which is a SaaS solution that enables you to', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'use IoT with minimal customization. And finally, there is Azure IoT Edge, which allows', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'IoT devices to do some of the calculations locally, instead of having to communicate', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'with the cloud for every operation. Trained ML models can even be deployed to edge', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'devices enabling capabilities such as image recognition in disconnected hardware.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Data Analytics', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'There are many services in Azure for doing data analytics, including Azure Data Factory', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'for moving and transforming data; Azure Analysis Services, which provides an in-', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'memory data analytics platform; and Azure Data Lake Analytics, which can perform U-', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'SQL jobs on Azure Data Lake Store. You can also take advantage of Azure Stream', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Analytics to analyze data on the fly and Azure Time Series Insights, which provides a', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'unique data analytics platform for time-based data that can store and analyze data and', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'can show information using its own data visualization engine. In addition, there is Azure', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Databricks, which offers a managed cluster of enhanced Apache Spark–based analytics', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'engines, and Azure HDInsight, which you can use to spin up managed clusters of open-', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'source data analytics platforms and tools, like Apache Storm, Apache Kafka, and', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Apache HBase.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '24', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Messaging', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure also provides services that can help you build scalable architectures with events', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'and messages. Azure Queue Storage and Azure Service Bus Topics and Queues can help', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'with that by providing queuing mechanisms that decouple your services. Azure Event', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Grid can help by subscribing to events, like blobs being added and pushing an event to', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'whoever is subscribed to it. And Azure Event Hubs can ingest massive amounts of data,', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'which you can process, filter, and store in your own time. Using messaging to', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'communicate between services in Azure allows you to handle load smoothly while also', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'preventing data loss in the event a service is unavailable.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Media Services', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Working with (streaming) media can be challenging. Azure Media Services can help you', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'by providing services like encoding, which encodes your media files into the file formats', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'and screen sizes they need to be. Azure Content Protection enables you to use DRM', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'technologies like PlayReady to make sure that your content is only used by authorized', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'users. With live streaming you can stream media worldwide at massive scale. And by', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'using Media Analytics you can enhance media by doing intelligent things like creating', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'subtitles for a movie based on speech.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Monitoring', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'And finally, you need to monitor your applications that run in Azure, to make sure that', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'they run smoothly. The monitoring tools in Azure fall under the umbrella of Azure', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Monitor. There are services like Azure Application Insights that can help you to monitor', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'every aspect of your application. There is also Azure Log Analytics, which plugs into', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'every Azure Service to gather diagnostics information, and Azure Network Watcher,', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'which can inspect network traffic from your VMs and over your Virtual Networks.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '25', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Figure 1 A sample monitoring dashboard', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Visual Studio App Center provides logging and monitoring as part of a fully featured', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'suite of tools for mobile applications. Azure Security Center, which is your one-stop-', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'shop for all the security aspects of all your services in Azure. Your logs can be visualized', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'using Azure Dashboards or Power BI and you can even trigger custom actions from log', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'events using Logic Apps.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '26', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Tools for developing, debugging\nand troubleshooting\nAs .NET developers and architects, we are spoiled with the incredible tooling of Visual', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Studio. This extends into the world of Azure, which includes many tools that can make', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'developing and troubleshooting in Azure easier and fun. Let’s explore these tools.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Visual Studio and Azure', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'We all love Visual Studio and Azure does too! If you run any version of Visual Studio', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '2019 or 2017 and enable the Azure workload, you’ll be able to seamlessly work with', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure. And if you can’t upgrade, that’s OK, we have you covered there, too. If you are', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'using Visual Studio 2015, you can download the Visual Studio 2015 Tools for Azure.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Project templates', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Out of the box, you get lots of project templates to work with. You can create web', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'applications for the cloud, Azure Cloud Services applications, Azure Functions, Azure', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'WebJobs, and much more.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '27', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Figure 2: Azure project templates in Visual Studio 2019 with Azure workload installed', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Cloud Explorer', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'As part of the Azure workload in Visual Studio, you get Cloud Explorer. You can use this', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'to navigate through all your Azure subscriptions and resources and take action, as in', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Figure 3, where you can attach a debugger to an App Service Web App.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'From Cloud Explorer, you can also do things like open an Azure SQL Database in the', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Visual Studio Server Explorer and upload files to Azure Storage.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'You can even connect to services to see their streaming logs and change application', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'settings and connection strings in App Service.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'G et started by managing your Azure resources with Cloud Explorer .', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '28', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Figure 3: Cloud Explorer in Visual Studio', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Publish to Azure', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Once you have the Azure workload enabled in Visual Studio, you can easily publish to', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure from various project types. The publish wizard has an option to publish to Azure', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'App Service (for example, host a web site). Or you can directly publish to specific', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'services like Azure Cloud Services. All with a few clicks.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Get started by using the Visual Studio Publish Azure Application wizard .', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '29', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Figure 4: Publish to Azure', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'For a more repeatable process you can set up an Azure DevOps pipeline from inside', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Visual Studio 2019 which will build, test, and deploy your application to Azure. The', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Pipeline will be kicked off every time there is a check-in to your source control ensuring', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'your application is always up to date.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '30', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Figure 5: Configure a DevOps Pipeline', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Snapshot Debugger', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'The Snapshot Debugger allows you to debug your application while it is running live in', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'production, without affecting its performance. This is great, because now you can debug', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'production without pausing the app when you hit a breakpoint. Debugging provides a', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'lot more information than diagnostic logs typically do.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '31', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Note that you do need Visual Studio Enterprise to use the Snapshot Debugger. Here’s', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'how it works:', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '1. Attach the snapshot debugger to your application process in Azure.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '2. Add a snappoint (different from a breakpoint).', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '3. When the snappoint is hit, a snapshot is taken.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '• The debugger quickly gathers all the information it needs about the call stack and', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'variables and lets the app continue to run.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '4. You can now view the snapshot and inspect everything that you normally would', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'when debugging, without holding up the application.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Get started by debugging snapshots on exceptions in .NET apps .', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Storage Explorer', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'The Azure Storage Explorer is a tool for managing your Azure Storage accounts. It’s a', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'free, standalone application from Microsoft that you can download here. You can use it', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'to create new blob containers, upload files, query through Table storage, and more.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'You can even use it to manage your Cosmos DB storage and create databases and', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'collections.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Get started with Storage Explorer .', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '32', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Figure 6: Storage Explorer', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Storage Emulator', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'In the Visual Studio Azure workload or in the Azure SDK, you’ll find the Azure storage', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'emulator, which you can use to develop locally against Azure Storage. You can access it', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'through Cloud Explorer just like you can access it in the Azure portal or through other', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'tools such as Storage Explorer.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'The Azure storage emulator works the same as Azure Storage in the cloud, including', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'how you authenticate to it. There are some obvious differences, like file size limitations', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'and the lack of geo-redundant scaling. And the emulator doesn’t support Azure Files.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Once you are done developing and testing locally, you can publish your application to', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'the cloud and use Azure Storage there.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Get started by configuring and using the storage emulator\nwith Visual Studio .', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Command-Line Interface', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'You can do everything you need to do in Azure from Visual Studio and the Azure', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'portal. But sometimes you want to run scripts to perform command-level operations,', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'like when you are working with containers. You can do that using the Azure Command-', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Line Interface, or CLI. You can install the Azure CLI on your local development', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '33', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'computer, use a pre-built Docker container, or use it from within the Azure portal,', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'where it is a part of Azure Cloud Shell.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Using the CLI in the Azure portal through Cloud Shell is very easy. You don’t have to', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'install anything and you don’t have to log in to your Azure Subscription because you’ve', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'already done that to get into the portal.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Figure 7: Azure Cloud Shell in the Azure portal', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Cloud Shell supports Bash and PowerShell as scripting languages. These might not', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'be things that you use daily as a .NET developer, but they are worth diving into because', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'they are powerful tools.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Once you are in the CLI, you can do anything from listing all the Azure resources you', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'have to provisioning new resources.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'You can also access Cloud Shell directly in the browser at https://shell.azure.com or via', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'mobile devices such as iOS and Android.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '34', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Functions Core Tools', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Functions run inside Azure App Service Function Apps and are powerful. You can', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'use them to run small pieces of code that get triggered by outside sources and bind to', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'things like Azure Blob storage or Azure Cosmos DB.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'The Azure Functions Core Tools enable you to develop Azure Functions locally. You can', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'run the local version of Azure Functions runtime on your development computer.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'With the Azure Functions Core Tools, you can develop and test your Azure Functions', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'locally. And when you’re done, you can publish them to Azure or use continuous', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'integration and continuous delivery to check your Azure Functions code and publish it', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'automatically to Azure.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Get started by creating your first function using Visual Studio and', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'test it locally .', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Cosmos DB Emulator', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'When you are using Azure Cosmos DB, you can use the Azure Cosmos DB Emulator to', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'develop locally. The emulator acts just like Cosmos DB would and even provides the', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'same interface as Cosmos DB does in the Azure portal.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Figure 8: Cosmos DB Emulator local interface', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '35', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'The Cosmos DB Emulator also shows up in the Cloud Explorer in Visual Studio, so that', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'you can easily manage it from there.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'By developing locally against the Cosmos DB emulator, you can develop without', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'incurring costs from a Cosmos DB in Azure. And when you are ready, you can deploy', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'your application to Azure and run it against Cosmos DB there, just by changing your', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'connection string.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Get started by using the Azure Cosmos DB Emulator', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'for local development and testing .', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure DevOps for build and deployment', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Once you are working on your application, it is vital to integrate your work with the work', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'of other developers (continuous integration).', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'It is vital to deploy that work to a central location, like an Azure Web App, so that you', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'can see that it works, and so that it can be tested and promoted through the different', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'environments and can be deployed to production (continuous delivery).', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'To make this work, you need to automatically integrate everybody’s work and deploy it.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Ideally, you would do these things continuously, whenever somebody commits new', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'work.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure DevOps, can help with that. It is an application lifecycle management system that', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'manages your work items and sprints, stores and manages your source code, builds', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'your code, and deploys it to wherever you want. The best part is, it is very easy to set up.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'You can put your source code in DevOps and manage it using the TFS or Git protocols.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Once you start committing changes, you can have those built by a simple build', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'pipeline that executes something like a Visual Studio build, just like you would on your', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'local development computer. You can create such a pipeline by just adding tasks in', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'the DevOps portal, like in Figure 9.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '36', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Figure 9: DevOps Build Pipeline', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'You can set your build up to compile your code and run your unit tests every time', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'somebody commits. This is continuous integration.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'And once the build is done, it can kick off a release pipeline that deploys your code to', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'environments including development, test, staging, and production. You can deploy', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'your code to anywhere: to on-premises resources or to the cloud. You can even have', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'permissions gates that require somebody like a product owner to approve the', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'deployment to production, putting them in control.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'You create a release pipeline in the same way as you create a build pipeline—by adding', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'tasks in the Azure DevOps portal, like in Figure 10.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '37', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Figure 10: Azure DevOps Release Pipeline', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure DevOps is a powerful tool that every .NET developer should have in their arsenal.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Now you no longer have an excuse to not do continuous integration and continuous', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'deployment.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Get started with Azure DevOps', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Download and read the free e-book about DevOps for a', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'microservices architecture .', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '38', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Summary and how to get started for free\nIn this guide, we’ve introduced the power that Azure can bring to your applications.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Using Azure, you can do incredible things with your applications—facial and speech', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'recognition, manage your devices on the Internet of Things in the cloud, scale as much', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'as you want, and pay for what you use.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'You’ve seen that Azure is a great place for .NET developers and architects and it', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'provides tools that have the same world-class quality and depth that you are used to', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'working with today. The days of having to write complicated “plumbing” yourself are', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'over. Now you can take advantage of a wealth of prebuilt solutions. Free yourself up to', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'work on the things that matter, and let Azure take care of the solved problems.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Keep learning with an Azure free account', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Do you have a Visual Studio Subscription? Activate your monthly Azure credit.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Sign up for an Azure free account and receive:', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '•  A $200 credit to use on any Azure product for 30 days', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '•  Free access to our most popular products for 12 months, including compute, storage,', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'networking, and database', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '•  More than 25 products that are always free, including Text Translator, Functions and Active', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Directory B2C', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Download and install language-specific SDKs and tools at:', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'https://azure.microsoft.com/downloads/', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '39', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'About the team', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Cesar, Michael, Beth and Barry are passionate about Microsoft Azure and would encourage you to reach\nout to them on Twitter for questions regarding this book.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Cesar de la Torre works for Microsoft Corp in Redmond, Seattle, in the .NET\nproduct team, focusing on .NET, Azure, Containers & Microservice-based\narchitectures and creating .NET Application Architecture guidance.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'You can reach him on Twitter @cesardelatorre or by following his blog at\nhttps://blogs.msdn.microsoft.com/cesardelatorre/.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Michael Crump works at Microsoft on the Azure platform and is a coder, blogger,\nand international speaker on various cloud development topics. He’s passionate\nabout helping developers understand the benefits of the cloud in a no-nonsense\nway.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'You can reach him on Twitter @mbcrump or by following his blog at\nhttps://www.michaelcrump.net.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Barry Luijbregts is an independent architect and software developer focused on\npreparing business applications and solutions for the cloud. A Microsoft Azure\nMVP, Barry is a skilled educator and active member of the community providing\nPluralsight cloud and developer-focused courses and on-site private training\nsessions for corporate groups. He records podcasts, founded an active .NET User', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Group, and leads technology bootcamps. Barry has a lifelong passion for technology and for IT in\nparticular. Technology drives his curiosity as he stays current and gains unique access to new\ntechnology through Microsoft early adoption programs. Understanding that software is an\ninvestment, Barry uses his knowledge of cloud direction to advise clients on forward-looking and\nsustainable long-term solutions. You can reach Barry on Twitter @AzureBarry and through his\nwebsite at https://www.azurebarry.com.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Beth Massi is the Product Marketing Manager for the .NET Platform and\nLanguages at Microsoft. She’s a long-time community champion for .NET\ndevelopers and on the Board of Directors for the .NET Foundation. You can reach\nher on Twitter @BethMassi.', 'task_item': False}, {'text': 'Azure Quick Start Guide for .NET Developers', 'task_item': False}, {'text': '40', 'task_item': False}]]}